I also remember when we got our first VCR. It was the mid 80s, behind the Iron Curtain. VCRs were luxury items, only available in special shops which required purchasing with dollars, and the exchange rate was criminal (you have no idea *how* criminal. I mean, a Polish living monthly salary translated into something like 5$). My parents shouldered the cost for my sake: to allow me to watch English-languages films and shows (on bootleg tapes), and improve my English skills beyond what was possible with written matter. Getting that VCR 40 years ago was one of the factors that contributed to my talking to you here today üôÇ

@Andrzej 
43D was definitely meant as a misdirection, most people would think of a GPS or airtag, not a VCR!

I have owned many over the years... most of them have auto tracking, some of the fancier ones have a button or dial where you can do it manually. It's purpose is to reposition the tape so you don't get any fuzzy lines at the bottom or top (or middle) of the picture. If your VCR had auto tracking you might only notice some fuzziness when you first hit play, and then it would adjust to a clear picture.

