@Lpr 

Oh, as a Polish person, I know *so many* people who speak Catholic! It is a very strange version of Polish, using antiquated vocabulary, and often used to justify some suspect things in the strangest of ways (love thy neighbor - unless they're gay! - that sort of thing).

As for Yiddish, I was fascinated by it when I was studying Polish 19th century history and learning German at the same time. Jews published many newspapers in Yiddish in Warsaw, and I loved reading original excerpts: they used a language both alien and familiar to me. The words were mostly German, but the whole thing was written using Polish phonetic transcription. For example, one of those newspapers was called "Jidisze cajtung". Really cool stuff for somebody like me, interested in people and cultures.

@DJ I notice some solvers complain about topics which are familiar to many New Yorkers but may not be to others.  I'm Irish-American and raised Catholic.  However, being a New Yorker, one absorbs a lot of Jewish culture and Yiddish terms.  As Lenny Bruce said, "If you're a goy from New York, you're a Jew.  If you a Jew from Minnesota, you're a goy."

New York  has a large Jewish population.  Makes sense to me the NEW YORK Times crossword would have answers which refer to Jewish culture and/or Yiddish words.

As an aside, I'm always wowed by solvers from other parts of the world who are able to complete a NYT puzzle because a lot of the puzzles contain a fair amount of answers related to US-centric sports and pop culture.  Really impressive

